# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 13 Dead End Drive — Global Project Guardrails (.cursorrules)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Scope  : Every file, every agent, every contributor, every CI pipeline.
# Status : ACTIVE — non-negotiable. Violations block merges.
# Updated: Phase 2.2 → 2.3 handoff
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 0 — Knowledge Base First (Pre-Mutation Requirement)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Before mutating ANY source file, every agent MUST:
#   1. Read /.context/system_state.md     → understand current phase and registry
#   2. Read /.context/api_contracts.md    → validate type changes against contracts
#   3. Read /.context/prompt_playbook.md  → learn what has already been tried
#   4. Read the target directory's .mdc file if one exists
#   5. Check /.context/rfc/               → understand historical design design invariants
#
# You are required to treat files inside `/.context/rfc/` as immutable technical debt
# and design invariants. Code generations must align with our recorded historical RFCs.
#
# Failure to read these files before editing is a protocol violation.
# The agent must self-report any context gaps before proceeding.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 1 — Strict TDD Workflow (Test-Driven Development)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# All implementation follows this exact order. No exceptions.
#
#   STEP 1 — SPEC FIRST
#     Write the failing test spec before writing any implementation code.
#     The spec must be committed and confirmed RED before Step 2 begins.
#
#   STEP 2 — MINIMAL IMPLEMENTATION
#     Write only the code necessary to make the failing tests pass.
#     Do not add logic not covered by an existing failing test.
#
#   STEP 3 — VERIFY GREEN
#     Run `npx vitest run --reporter=verbose` and confirm 0 failures.
#     Present the full terminal output. Never claim tests pass without evidence.
#
#   STEP 4 — REGRESSION CHECK
#     All previously passing tests must still pass after every new implementation.
#     A new green test that causes an old test to fail = BLOCKED.
#
#   STEP 5 — REFACTOR (optional)
#     Clean up only after the suite is fully green. No logic changes during refactor.
#
# Anti-patterns that are FORBIDDEN:
#   ❌ Writing implementation before writing the spec
#   ❌ Skipping the terminal output verification step
#   ❌ Merging when any test is red
#   ❌ Mocking the system under test inside the test itself

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 2 — Zero Loose Types
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The TypeScript configuration enforces:
#   "strict": true
#   "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true
#   "noImplicitAny": true
#   "noImplicitReturns": true
#   "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true
#
# At the code level:
#   ❌ FORBIDDEN: `any`            — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
#   ❌ FORBIDDEN: `as any`         — use a properly typed assertion or refactor
#   ❌ FORBIDDEN: `// @ts-ignore`  — fix the actual type error
#   ❌ FORBIDDEN: `// @ts-expect-error` without an inline justification comment
#   ❌ FORBIDDEN: Loose object literals that widen to `{}` or `object`
#   ✅ REQUIRED:  Discriminated unions for all multi-variant payloads (e.g. PlayCardPayload)
#   ✅ REQUIRED:  `as const` on every tuple used as a union source
#   ✅ REQUIRED:  Explicit return type annotations on all exported functions
#
# Card action payloads use STRICT discriminated unions. Each cardType variant
# carries ONLY the fields it requires — no nullable cross-field pollution.
# See src/types/socket-events.ts for the canonical pattern.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 3 — Language & Runtime Standards
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   - TypeScript 5.5+, strict mode enforced by tsconfig.json
#   - Node.js 24+, ESM modules only ("type": "module" in package.json)
#   - All import paths MUST use .js extensions (NodeNext module resolution)
#   - Test framework: Vitest 2.x only — no Jest, no Mocha
#   - No CommonJS require() anywhere in the codebase

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 4 — Pure Functional Engine Pipeline
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# All engine functions are PURE:
#   Input:  (state: GameState, ...eventArgs) → Output: GameState (new reference)
#   The input `state` object is NEVER mutated.
#   All state updates use structural spread cloning.
#
# Enforced pipeline order for every player turn:
#   1. Guard:    Turn ownership, character eligibility, alive status, dice present
#   2. Validate: Path structure (empty / duplicate / origin / toCell mismatch)
#   3. Validate: Path contiguity via board adjacency graph + blocker scan
#   4. Apply:    applyMove()      — pure position update, no side effects
#   5. Evaluate: evaluateTraps()  — auto-trigger post-condition (Phase 2.2) ✅
#   6. Evaluate: evaluateWin()    — win/loss resolution (Phase 2.4) 🔲
#
# Side effects (WS broadcast, DB write, logging) are FORBIDDEN inside engine functions.
# The transport layer calls engine functions and handles their output.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 5 — Module Boundaries (Hard Walls)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Each engine module has a single, non-overlapping responsibility:
#
#   src/engine/moveCharacter.ts    → Path validation + pawn position update only
#   src/engine/trapEvaluator.ts    → Trap fire cascade, portrait rotation, player elimination
#   src/engine/detectiveTrack.ts   → Detective step advance + mass elimination
#   src/engine/playCard.ts         → Card action dispatch + discriminated union validation
#   src/engine/winCondition.ts     → Win/loss resolution only
#   src/engine/turnOrchestrator.ts → Cross-module pipeline composition (Phase 2.5)
#
# Cross-module calls MUST be made via the orchestrator, not via direct imports
# between peer engine modules (prevents circular dependency chains).
# Exception: moveCharacter.ts may directly call evaluateTraps() per Phase 2.2 design.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 6 — Error Handling
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   ✅ All engine errors MUST throw `EngineError` (src/engine/EngineError.ts)
#   ✅ EngineError.code MUST be a valid SocketErrorCode literal from enums.ts
#   ✅ The WS transport layer catches EngineError and maps .code → ErrorResponse
#   ❌ Never throw raw `new Error(...)` from engine functions
#   ❌ Never swallow errors silently — every catch must rethrow or handle explicitly
#   ❌ Never use console.error as a substitute for structured error handling

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 7 — Testing Standards
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   - Test files live in: src/__tests__/engine/
#   - Fixture factories live in: src/__tests__/fixtures/gameState.fixtures.ts
#   - NEVER inline mock objects inside spec files — always import from fixtures
#   - Use the `expectEngineError(fn, code)` helper — never `.toThrow(string)`
#     Reason: .toThrow(string) matches the error MESSAGE; we assert error CODES
#   - Every spec file has a one-line comment at the top naming the function under test
#   - Describe blocks map 1:1 to behavioral domains (not implementation internals)
#   - Each `it()` block asserts exactly ONE behavior — no compound assertions
#   - `beforeEach` is used for state setup — never share mutable state across tests

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 8 — Naming Conventions
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   Engine functions  : camelCase verb+noun  (moveCharacter, evaluateTraps, advanceDetective)
#   Types/Interfaces  : PascalCase           (GameState, TrapState, MovePawnEvent)
#   Const tuple items : SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (CHANDELIER, GAME_OVER, READY)
#   Test fixtures     : make-prefix          (makeGameState, makeCell, makeTrap)
#   Engine errors     : SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (INVALID_MOVE, NOT_YOUR_TURN, GAME_ALREADY_OVER)
#   Spec files        : <subject>.spec.ts    (moveCharacter.spec.ts, trapAutoTrigger.spec.ts)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# RULE 9 — Living Documentation Maintenance
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These files MUST be kept current at every phase gate:
#
#   /.context/system_state.md      — Phase status, module registry, resolved constraints
#   /.context/api_contracts.md     — All public type interfaces and their change log
#   /.context/prompt_playbook.md   — Archive of successful prompt patterns per milestone
#   /.context/ai_skills.md         — AI agent role definitions and expertise profiles
#
# An agent that modifies src/types/ without updating api_contracts.md is in violation.
# An agent that completes a phase gate without updating system_state.md is in violation.
